description.text:
M&P_940_SHIELD_V1-2-1.stl - This model is the newer model that has increased surface area around the top trigger pin. Even though the last model never failed for me, I increased the structure just for piece of mind. Still does NOT have a safety.
https://youtu.be/643-sETmlqs

M&P_940_SHIELD_NOSAFETY_V1-8.stl - This model currently has no safety built into it like the previous trigger for the full size. I am currently working on that now.

I designed a flat faced trigger for my full size handgun and loved it so I decided to proceed with my compact weapon also. I have found the flat face helps me with smoother trigger pulls without wiggling the nose of the weapon in any other direction than it should be. Plus it is just a lot of fun to see if I am able to design something this intricate and have it work. This is not designed to be a OEM part replacement since it is just a 3ds printed part so USER BEWARE! you are using this piece at your own discretion. Thanks for looking!

comments.text: My printer doesn't have a heated bed and, at the time, the M3D company was still fine tuning the software for other problems (warping, prints not sticking properly, etc...). description.text:
After reading some papers on cooling the human body through pulse points I decided to build this prototype.

The human body has several pulse points, one of the major ones is in the wrist where blood flows very close to the skin. When these areas are cooled the entire body is effectively cooled as the cooled blood is pumped around bringing down your body temperature.

If this ends up working I wanted to make a portable rig to wear while riding my motorcycle in 100F+ weather.

This uses a United states $1 coin and it fits quite snugly with a small bead of hot glue to seal it. My print actually leaked through a few of the layers very slowly, a drop every 30 seconds or so, but that's only because I had recently changed filaments and the new filament needs to be printed at a higher temperature, that is fixed now.

It needs more work, the hose barbs should be made glue in instead of one piece so they can print vertical so they stay round.

As far as testing I pumped tap water, around 75F through it with a small pump at a quite slow rate, the output tube was barely a stream, and I applied a 40W soldering iron to the coin for several minutes and you could put your finger on the coin right next to the soldering iron and it stayed cool to the touch.

EDIT
Added a spiral based cooler in an attempt to increase flow. It has been printed and printed perfectly, but has not been tested yet.

A spool holder for the Prusa i2.  It rolls very easy and gives little rolling friction.  Easy to switch out spools too!

Print two of the pieces. Put them anywhere on the 5/16" or 8mm threaded rods atop the Prusa i2. Bolt them down with the M3's
It uses (what I used anyways):
1x 5/16" threaded rod
4 x 5/16" nuts
2 x 608 bearings (I used 608zzg)
8 x M3x18mm (I used M3x20)
8 x M3 washers
8 x M3 nuts
I tried many different spool managment jigs from here and they all gave slightly too much friction for my liking. So I made my own and it has been working flawlessly for 4 months. Put some tap on the foward threaded rod to reduce friction even more. At first I suspected it would be wobbly, but it is actually very rigid with the M3 screws on the bottom.
I have used Octave ABS and JustPLA spools and it accomodates both very nicely.
Happy printing!

description.text:
IMPORTANT NOTE: If you use PLA (like most new people do with printing), use your slicer program to increase the size of this spacer to 102% before printing. With ABS it should be very close depending on the steps and tolerance of your printer. Check it with a caliper, 4.9 to 5.1 should be fine.

Those with a new Prusa kit or Prusa clone kit setup many times find that once their Z axis raises up 10mm or more, the motors seem to start "skipping" or one side refuses to rise up properly. One common cause of this is the threaded rod being pushed into the spring blocks too far (the other being the two sides not level with the printer itself). Both the motor shaft and the threaded rod should only go into the spring block at most 6mm. Since most people are able to do very small prints up to 6-10mm before the Z axis starts binding, this is a VERY simple 5mm spacer, with an 8mm hole in the middle (meaning it can be used with either 5mm or 8mm shafts).
Then once it prints, turn off power to your printer, loosen one side, slide this spacer over the motor shaft the height of the spacer (5mm), and using a very fine pointed sharpie marker, mark the other side. Slide the spring block onto it to that point and tighten down. Then do the same with the threaded rod. go to the other side and repeat until all 4 are spaced into the spring block the same amount.
Then make sure to re-level your Z axis with the printer (not the table it sits on), turn the power back on and adjust the Z stop and bed level height since this likely changed.

title: RedSnapper - The Compact and Precise Pin Header Adjustment Tool - 2.54mm Pitch

description.text:
After tweaking Oomlout's WHSN slightly just yesterday it managed to wangle its way into the part of my brain that obsesses over details. The pin headers we sell are 40 pin and the WHSN will do a good job of snapping them, but why does it have to be so big? The RedSnapper is half the length and has been corrected to a proper golden ratio, and therefore uses nearly a quarter of the material to do the same job. Also the bill of materials is smaller. 4-5 M3 Screws and nuts and you're golden. The slider is longer than the body so it can't get stuck inside, also now you measure from the end of the slider rather than from a line towards the end. We vector cut two lines at the end of the slides so you can pull it with your nail.
Extra lines have been added for measuring and sensible 10 and 20 markers provided. The world is so much easier in decimal!
Let us know what you think. Due to popular demand http://www.phenoptix.com/products/redsnapper-the-compact-and-precise-pin-header-adjustment-tool-2-54mm-pitch

description.text:
These parts are to use with a formaker 4-in-1 printer from CTC.
I didn't have a before and after print, but I found a similar thing here on thingiverse for the CTC flashforge clone.
The Formaker is mostly similar but has different dimensions, also the front has a angled edge, So the old "stabilizer" from the other guys didn't worked.
I have completely redesigned so it will fit very well.

Printer:

Be3D DeeGreen

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.15mm

Infill:

40 - 50 %

Notes:

Normaly no supports are used, only for the z-stabilizer big part. If you have good bridging it is not required to use supports at all.

Printing

Please check the images for the rotation settings, most items are not just printable without supports in the original orientation.

Introduction

For mounting.

Bearings
I used for Y Axe: 16mm outer and 5mm inner diameter
I used for Z Axe: 22mm outer and 8mm inner diameter

Pre info
i only use m3 screws.
I only use m3 security nuts.

If you see the hexagon extrusion, just push longer m3 screw into the holer from the back, place a nut, tighten the screw, align the nut with the extrusion and tighten the nut until it hits the end, now unscrew it without lifting the nut. the nut will now be in place and later in the screwing process just use the m3 screw. You do not need to hold the nut in place.

While moving Y axis it is helpful to not push it to hard, else it could be that the plastic support can break. Just shake a bit on it from the left to the right. you will recognize a "sweat spot" where you can push the shaft trough.

Y-Axe
Remove the belt spring which tightens the y-belt. then remove at the front and in the back the screws which holds the belt gear. also remove the Y-Stepper motor.
Now remove the Y belt on the left and right.
To remove the y shaft on the front and back, choose a small 3mm diameter metal stick and use a hammer to loosen the gears from the shaft. Then remove all gears and the shaft. Place the stabilizer onto the shaft and then put the gears back. Now just attach the y-shafts to the left and right small bearing and tighten the back gears and one front gear. attach the belt again (For me the belt could not get into the same tooth position where it was, because the y.shaft does not warp anymore and is more away. I lost ~2 tooth)
After this, just put on the other belt.
Now tight up the belt with the springs and to get correct and good gear positions you have to loosen now the front gear screws and rotate it a bit, due to the tighten spring attached the gear will rotate into a good position. Tighten the screws up again.
Finished :)

Z-axis
Remove the top 4 screws which holds the support shafts left and right for Z.
Place the bearing holder onto the z-axis TR screw.
push one metal plate, which was attached to the left or right side with the 4 screws you loosen, into one side of the z stabilizer so that it fit well into the notch.
use one stabilizer support and place it behind.
Screw up this side now but not to hard, just that it will not get out of the notch.
Now place the other side metal plate into the free notch and slide the last support stabilizer into place.Screw it up like the first one. use now 4 screwns to screw the bearing holder to the stabilizer. Now tighten one screw at left support shaft, then one on the right shaft, second screw left and right and in a cross way the bearing holder.

Have fun.

description.text:
I needed a way to run wires around the ROSTOCK MAX V2 I am building, I was just not ready to zip tie the wires here and there. And adding in some new wiring for LED lighting I wanted to keep it clean and organized.

So I thought I would make a couple of wire looms to use, not just for the printer build but also for a few ARDUINO projects I am planning.

After making my first print I decided to make some other sizes so I thought a CUSTOMIZER THING file would be nice to have.
SOOO this is my first effort at a CUSTOMIZER THING, interesting experience.

I do note that the resizing is slow do to method of sizing used in OPENSCAD rendering.
So be patient if you use.

Printer:

FLASHFORGE CREATOR PRO (2016)

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

standard

Infill:

20-25%

Notes:

rafts were to much trouble and it removed easy enough.

A bit hard to get the tree supports out, not that many to remove but they are inside and need to be pushed out.
I used a long small screw driver.

I started with a square tube and a slot in one corner to slide the wires in. But felt the build would be a bit complex with supports. I could fix this by two piece design,but I wanted a one piece so dropped the idea of a slide on top for the square.
This moved my design to a triangle (in OPENSCAD a three sided cylinder) .

I went with staggered fingers to allow wires yo be laid in in a zigzag fashion one at a time or the fingers allow enough flew to spread the opening as you feed the wires along.

I added side holes for ability to drop out wires along the loom.

And added bottom holes if I want to mount with screws to the cabinet walls, but plan to use most of the time 3M double side tape used for applying car trim and such.

To make it resize I tried for first time "multmatrix" to rescale it. A handy transform for scaling.

I had to try making my first CUSTOMIZER THING and this seemed like a good item to try.

First try with CUSTOMIZER, had to learn some new things there.
It runs a bit slow, a lot of calculations.

plan to add option for side holes or no side holes and maybe resize them.
I added them for dropping wires and to save filament (like it saves a lot)

description.text:
I had to move things around when I installed the Mamba Monster motor and ESC, and ran 6S for speed runs. Now that I've gotten the speed runs out of the way, I had to come up with a more conventional setup. Thanks to the giant ESC that Mamba provides, that meant relocating the receiver, the best alternative place is in the front. I made this mount to hold the ESC in front of the steering servo. It was a a little thin around the front screw holes because the chassis narrows, so the front has a slight overhang (see picture of overhang on chassis). If I decide to rebuild this I'll hug against the chassis and use a more durable Alloy 910 filament or something.

Designed with 123d, and thingiverse doesn't allow upload of 123d files, so if you want to modify this, ask and I'll send you the design files.

description.text:
I needed flanges for a few NEMA 17 Planetary Geared motors that didn't have the mounting plates for 'standard' NEMA 17 layout.

I found Glacians22's part, but there were 2 issues with it, and one modification I wanted to add:
1) It was not thick enough to completly countersink the screws used to mount the adapter to the motor.
2) The hole for the stepper was too tight - I opened it up a little bit to account for the size of the plastic. (And still had to file it some)
3) For the mod, I wanted to add countersunk areas to put M3 nuts.

In the pictures, the WHITE plate is my re-mix, and the BLACK plate is the original one (note that the screw heads are exposed)

If you are going to use the version with the countersunk nuts, you'll need 4 M3 nuts for each mount (either standard nuts or Nylock will work fine - it's your choice)

title: Replay XD to Binocular Lens Adapter

description.text:
An adaptor tube to fit an old binocular objective I had lying around to a Replay XD 1080 camera for high zoom levels. The lens holder had a M40x1.5mm thread which screws into the matching end and the XD1080 is a snug fit in the opposite end. The original camera lens is removed by moderate heating (to soften glue) and unscrewing after the protective bezel is unscrewed. The flat polycarboante window and bezel is then replaced to protect the sensor inside.

The outer diameter has been chosen as 35mm as it is a common scope size and various mounting options are available.

Chromatic aberration is a big problem for single lens, high magnification systems. It can be processed in software to some degree, but a monochromatic filter might be the easiest solution.

Not really satisfied with the image quality, too much light leakage and my magnification is probably too high to get a good image. I was using white filament, painted black. Now I have some black filament I might have another go. Just publishing this model as an example for now.

title: Pretty Good LED Bar and Okay Fan Shroud for Makerfarm Pegasus

description.text:
This is a kit of upgrades for the Makerfarm Pegasus with the metal X motor bracket. Included is a simple 3mm LED light bar that press-fits onto the X bracket. (I included a wood version of the LED bar, assuming it's the same offsets.) I also included a basic 40mm fan shroud for cooling the print at the hot end. The fan shroud should work for the standard extruder regardless of the motor mount.

Edit: Changed title; no mods to design files.

Printer:

Makerfarm Pegasus 10

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

50-100%

Notes:

The little LED light covers will print better at 0.1mm. The fan mounting tab may do better at 0.1mm also.

Assembly

The LED bar takes three 3mm LEDs. I powered mine from the 5V and GND pins of an AUX connector on the RAMPS board. Since my LEDs are 3.1V and 20 mA LEDs, I used a 75-ohm current limit resistor on the anode of each LED. Refer to the schematic for details.

I don't like the LEDs shining up into my face, so I included three little covers which you can glue over the backs of each LED.

To install the LED bar, just press it up onto the bottom edge of the motor mount.

The cooling fan shroud has three parts: the shroud itself, the L-shaped mounting bar, and a mounting tab.
1) Insert the tab into the shroud and glue it in place.
2) Slide the 40mm fan into the shroud's receptacle. No screws required; it should press into place with a bit of resistance.
2) The tab takes an M3 locknut. Bolt the shroud's tab to the L-shaped arm, so that the assembly will hang from the M4 nut on the extruder. (See the picture for details.)
4) Remove the M4 nut on the extruder, install the L-arm, and reinstall the nut.

The airflow should point under the hotend.

LED Schematic

comments.text: Good idea. Potting the wires would clean it up nicely too. In fact, brushing some silicone/caulk inside the mounting slot would help hold the LED bar in place. I went with 5V and parallel LEDs because of all the open AUX headers on my printer.
comments.author: bhunt

comments.text: This also drops you current draw by 66.6% since Kirchhoff's Law tells use current adds in parallel circuits and remains the same in a series circuit, also your resistor value is way too low, it's more like 30 mA which will burn out those LEDs in no time. the difference in lumens between 15 mA and 20 mA is so miniscule, it's not worth pressing them. The closest common value would be 150 ohms which will give you about 13 mA and 100 ohms would get you 19 mA. If you go with the series circuit and 12v you would need a single 180 ohm and that will get you 15mA on the nose.
comments.author: bhunt

comments.text: Wire your LED's in series and use a single current limiting resistor and then just splice it into the 12v lead to the E3D fan. That will save a couple of components and save having to run a new 5v wire. To make a really nice looking finished project get some of that liquid black tape and a small paint brush and 'pot' the wiring
